{"type":"message","id":"0c221a42","parentId":"fa274283","timestamp":"2026-03-17T01:50:20.225Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Explaining config mappings**\n\nI think we have enough information now. I should focus on explaining just the config mappings. I want to mention that some schema lookups failed, probably due to differing paths. I realize I don't need any further tools for this. To start, I need to use the reply tag, and I want to make sure my response is concise yet useful for clarity.\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] 行，那我只解释，不动机器。\n\n把这次报告里的问题，映射到 **OpenClaw 里真正对应的配置项**，大概是下面这张脑图：\n\n---\n\n## 1）Feishu 群组策略过松\n**对应配置：**\n- `channels.feishu.groupPolicy`\n\n我查到 schema 里这个字段只支持 3 个值：\n- `open`\n- `allowlist`\n- `disabled`\n\n### 这三个值的意思\n- **open**  \n  群里默认可用。风险最高，尤其当代理还能 `exec/read/write/process`。\n- **allowlist**  \n  只有白名单群可用。通常这是更稳的折中方案。\n- **disabled**  \n  彻底禁群，只保留私聊。\n\n### 为什么报告会报它\n因为你当前是 `open`。  \n这在“个人私聊助手”场景不算离谱，但在“可能被拉进群、群里消息复杂”的场景里，就会放大提示注入和误触发风险。\n\n---\n\n## 2）沙箱太松 / 主代理权限太大\n**对应配置主线：**\n- `agents.defaults.sandbox`\n- 下面可见的子项有：\n  - `agents.defaults.sandbox.mode`\n  - `agents.defaults.sandbox.workspaceAccess`\n  - `agents.defaults.sandbox.sessionToolsVisibility`\n  - `agents.defaults.sandbox.scope`\n  - `agents.defaults.sandbox.perSession`\n  - `agents.defaults.sandbox.workspaceRoot`\n\n我查了 schema，`agents.defaults.sandbox` 这个对象是存在的，说明报告里提到的“sandbox=off/偏松”确实是这一块在起作用。\n\n### 你可以这样理解这组配置\n- **mode**  \n  决定沙箱强度/是否启用。  \n  报告里说的 `sandbox=off`，本质就是这一级没收紧。\n- **workspaceAccess**  \n  决定沙箱里对 workspace 的访问方式。  \n  一般是为了让代理“只在工作区里做事”，别碰外部目录。\n- **scope / perSession / workspaceRoot**  \n  是控制沙箱作用范围、是否每个会话独立、根目录在哪。\n\n### 为什么它重要\n如果这里很松，再叠加高权限工具：\n- `exec`\n- `process`\n- `read`\n- `write`\n- `edit`\n\n那代理一旦在复杂上下文里被带偏，影响就不只是“说错话”，而是可能 **碰命令、碰文件、碰工作区外的内容**。\n\n---\n\n## 3）文件系统边界太宽\n报告提到的是：\n\n- `fs.workspaceOnly=false`\n\n### 这代表什么\n意思很直白：  \n**文件系统工具不只限于 workspace。**\n\n也就是代理不一定只在：\n- `/root/.openclaw/workspace`\n\n里活动，还可能读到别的路径。\n\n### 为什么这很敏感\n你这个环境本来就是高信任的个人助手环境。  \n如果再叠加：\n- 群聊开放\n- 无沙箱/弱沙箱\n- 文件系统不限 workspace\n\n那整体信任边界就会很松。\n\n### 这里有个说明\n我直接查 `fs.workspaceOnly` 的 schema 路径时没查到，说明：\n- 要么这个字段在当前版本 schema 的路径不是这么写\n- 要么它是运行时/兼容层里生效，但不在公开 schema 的这个位置\n\n**但不影响理解**：  \n报告已经明确把它识别成一个有效风险点，含义就是“文件访问范围过大”。\n\n---\n\n## 4）Gateway 认证限流没配\n**对应配置：**\n- `gateway.auth.rateLimit`\n\n我查到 schema 里这项存在，而且子项很清楚：\n\n- `gateway.auth.rateLimit.maxAttempts`\n- `gateway.auth.rateLimit.windowMs`\n- `gateway.auth.rateLimit.lockoutMs`\n- `gateway.auth.rateLimit.exemptLoopback`\n\n### 这几个字段的意思\n- **maxAttempts**  \n  时间窗内最多允许尝试几次\n- **windowMs**  \n  统计时间窗\n- **lockoutMs**  \n  超限后锁多久\n- **exemptLoopback**  \n  是否放过本机回环地址\n\n### 为什么报告会报\n不是说你已经被爆破了，  \n而是：**如果 gateway 暴露在非本机地址上，没有认证限流就少一层门槛。**\n\n---\n\n## 5）节点 denyCommands 配置无效\n**对应配置：**\n- `gateway.nodes.denyCommands`\n\n我查到 schema 里它是：\n- 一个字符串数组\n- 并且提示里写得很明确：**精确按命令名匹配**\n\n示例提示接近这个意思：\n- 要写像 `system.run` 这种**完整命令名**\n- 不是模糊匹配\n- 也不会去理解 shell 文本内容\n\n### 这意味着什么\n如果你 denylist 里写了：\n- 错别字\n- 不存在的命令名\n- 以为能模糊匹配的名字\n\n那实际上 **不会生效**。\n\n### 报告为什么会点它\n因为审计器发现你配置里某些 deny 项“看起来像想拦，但名字不对”。\n\n---\n\n## 6）`/root/.openclaw/credentials` 权限不合规\n这个不是 OpenClaw 配置项，而是 **宿主机文件权限**。\n\n我顺手查了当前实际权限：\n- `/root/.openclaw/credentials` = **755**\n\n### 这为什么会被报\n因为这个目录按常识应该更严，通常建议：\n- **700**\n\n### 两者区别\n- `755`：其他用户可读可执行目录结构\n- `700`：只有 root 自己能进\n\n如果里面放的是：\n- 凭证\n- allowlist\n- token\n- 认证材料\n\n那 `755` 确实偏宽。\n\n---\n\n## 7）插件/Skill 被命中“危险模式”\n这个不完全是配置项，更像 **代码/供应链审计结果**。\n\n报告里点了两类：\n- `env-harvesting`\n- `dangerous-exec`\n\n### 它们通常意味着什么\n- **env-harvesting**  \n  插件/skill 读取环境变量，可能包括 API key、token、endpoint\n- **dangerous-exec**  \n  代码里存在命令执行路径\n\n### 这不等于恶意\n很多正常插件也会命中，比如：\n- 需要从环境变量里拿 token\n- 需要调用本地命令行工具\n\n但安全审计的意思是：\n> 这些组件需要你“明确地信任”，而不是默认无条件信任。\n\n### 对应到配置层面的含义\n不是“改一个字段就好了”，而是两件事：\n1. **减少这些插件在宽松上下文里可达**\n2. **把来源、版本、权限边界收紧**\n\n---\n\n## 8）“tool policy permissive” 的实际含义\n报告里说插件工具在 permissive policy 下可能可达。\n\n这通常不是单个字段能解释完，而是下面几块一起作用：\n- agent 默认工具集\n- sandbox\n- fs 边界\n- channel 暴露范围\n- 插件是否被主代理直接继承\n\n### 你可以把它理解成\n不是某个工具“坏”，  \n而是 **太多能力默认能被碰到**。\n\n---\n\n# 如果只讲“这几个配置项分别在防什么”\n可以压缩成一句人话：\n\n- `channels.feishu.groupPolicy`  \n  防**群聊误触发 / 群内提示注入**\n- `agents.defaults.sandbox.*`  \n  防**代理直接碰宿主机**\n- `fs.workspaceOnly`  \n  防**读写越界到工作区外**\n- `gateway.auth.rateLimit.*`  \n  防**认证暴力尝试**\n- `gateway.nodes.denyCommands`  \n  防**节点侧高风险命令被调用**\n- `/root/.openclaw/credentials` 权限  \n  防**本机其他用户窥读敏感目录**\n- 插件/skill 命中 `env-harvesting` / `dangerous-exec`  \n  防的是**供应链和插件侧信任过宽**\n\n---\n\n# 这次报告里，最关键的组合风险\n不是某一个字段单独爆炸，而是这几个一起出现：\n\n- `channels.feishu.groupPolicy = open`\n- `sandbox` 偏松\n- `fs.workspaceOnly = false`\n- 主代理能碰高权限工具\n\n这四个叠在一起，才是它为什么会把“配置基线”打成黄/橙色。\n\n---\n\n# 你如果后面要改，我建议先按这个顺序理解\n1. **先收入口**：群聊策略  \n2. **再收执行面**：sandbox  \n3. **再收文件边界**：workspace only  \n4. **再补外围防护**：auth rate limit  \n5. **最后清理细项**：denyCommands、插件版本、目录权限\n\n如果你要，我下一条可以继续给你出一个**“最小改动版配置建议”**，还是只解释，不直接动。"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":355,"output":2163,"cacheRead":39168,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41686,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773712164929}}
{"type":"message","id":"1d1a2bb3","parentId":"0c221a42","timestamp":"2026-03-17T01:54:43.773Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b54bf08e700bcb2768ac7914a229\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"sender\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-17 09:54 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"name\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b54bf08e700bcb2768ac7914a229]\nou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3: ok"}],"timestamp":1773712483771}}
{"type":"message","id":"b15e77fb","parentId":"1d1a2bb3","timestamp":"2026-03-17T01:55:41.492Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to provide an answer before any pending explanation. It seems that there’s no need for more tools, but I could mention that I checked the schema to ensure everything is squared away. It's important to keep this efficient and focus on what’s necessary. I need to remember to use the correct reply tag as it might be critical for this situation. I'll keep it straightforward!\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] 行，我只解释，不动配置。\n\n我把几个关键项对应到 OpenClaw 配置上了，给你翻成人话：\n\n---\n\n## 1) `channels.feishu.groupPolicy`\n可选值我已经查到是：\n\n- `open`\n- `allowlist`\n- `disabled`\n\n### 这三个分别啥意思\n- **open**\n  - 任何满足平台触发条件的群，都可能和机器人互动\n  - 方便，但风险最高\n- **allowlist**\n  - 只有你明确放进白名单的群才能用\n  - 这是最常见、也最稳的群聊方案\n- **disabled**\n  - 群聊里彻底不用，只允许私聊\n  - 最保守\n\n### 为什么你这次被打告警\n因为你现在是 **`open`**。  \n如果再叠加高权限工具，就等于：\n\n> 输入来源更杂 + 机器人可做的事更多\n\n所以扫描器会直接把它当成高风险入口。\n\n---\n\n## 2) `agents.defaults.sandbox`\n这个是 **代理默认沙箱配置**。\n\n我查到它下面主要有这些字段：\n- `mode`\n- `workspaceAccess`\n- `sessionToolsVisibility`\n- `scope`\n- `perSession`\n- `workspaceRoot`\n\n### 它本质上管什么\n一句话：\n\n> 机器人干活时，被关在多大的“笼子”里。\n\n### 重点理解\n- **sandbox 开 / 收紧**\n  - 就像给代理戴护栏\n  - 即便它想执行命令、操作文件，也只能在受限范围里动\n- **sandbox 关 / 太松**\n  - 它就更像直接拿着宿主机权限在跑\n\n### 为什么报告里提 `sandbox=off`\n因为这意味着：\n- 一旦被坏输入诱导\n- 风险不是“说错话”\n- 而是可能变成“真去执行东西”\n\n这就是它比普通提示注入更吓人的原因。\n\n---\n\n## 3) `fs.workspaceOnly=false`\n这个虽然我没查到 schema 路径，但结合报告语义很明确：\n\n### 它在说什么\n- **workspaceOnly=true**\n  - 文件访问限制在工作区里\n  - 比如只准碰 `/root/.openclaw/workspace`\n- **workspaceOnly=false**\n  - 代理不只可以碰工作区，理论上还能往外读更多路径\n\n### 风险点\n如果机器人既能读写文件，又不限制在 workspace：\n- 误读系统文件\n- 误碰凭证目录\n- 被诱导去扫更广目录\n\n都会变得更现实。\n\n所以这项不是“功能坏了”，而是：\n**边界画得太大。**\n\n---\n\n## 4) `gateway.auth.rateLimit`\n这个 schema 我查到了，下面有：\n\n- `maxAttempts`\n- `windowMs`\n- `lockoutMs`\n- `exemptLoopback`\n\n### 它是干嘛的\n这是 **网关认证限流**。\n\n可以理解成：\n- 一段时间内最多允许尝试几次登录/认证\n- 超了就锁一会儿\n- 本机回环地址要不要豁免\n\n### 为什么会被报问题\n如果这个没配，而你的 gateway 又不是只在本机内网用，那别人试口令/试认证的成本就会低很多。\n\n不是说现在一定有人在打你，\n而是说：\n\n> 门口没装“连续输错就锁门”的机制。\n\n---\n\n## 5) `gateway.nodes.denyCommands`\n这个 schema 我也查到了，它是个 **字符串数组**，而且提示里写得很清楚：\n\n> 必须是精确命令名匹配  \n> 例如：`system.run`\n\n### 这是什么意思\n你在 denyCommands 里写的东西，必须是**系统认得的命令名**。  \n如果你写错了、写成别名、或者写成 shell 文本，它不会按你想的那样生效。\n\n### 报告里“有无效项”的真实含义\n不是节点已经执行了危险命令。  \n而是：\n\n> 你以为自己封住了某些命令，但其中一部分 deny 项名字不对，实际上没封住。\n\n这类问题很隐蔽，因为看配置表面上像“写了”，实际上是“白写”。\n\n---\n\n## 6) `/root/.openclaw/credentials` 权限 755\n这个我也顺手核了一下，当前确实是：\n\n- `755 root:root /root/.openclaw/credentials`\n\n### 这代表什么\n目录权限 `755` 的意思大致是：\n- owner 可读写执行\n- group 可读执行\n- others 可读执行\n\n### 为什么不合规\n如果这里面放的是：\n- 凭证\n- allowlist\n- 访问控制文件\n- 认证相关材料\n\n那 `755` 就偏宽了。  \n安全扫描通常会希望这种目录至少更收紧，比如 `700`。\n\n### 风险是什么\n不是说“别人已经读到了”，而是：\n**本机其他非 root 用户理论上不该拥有这类目录的遍历/读取能力。**\n\n---\n\n# 你这次报告的本质，翻成一句话\n不是“发现入侵”，而是：\n\n> **当前 OpenClaw 更像给自己用的高权限全能助手配置，但安全巡检是按更严格的生产/暴露场景标准在看。**\n\n所以它会抓住这些点：\n- 群入口太开\n- 沙箱太松\n- 文件访问边界太大\n- 网关限流没上\n- 凭证目录权限不够严\n- denylist 里有写了等于没写的项\n\n---\n\n# 如果你只想知道“先看哪两个最值钱”\n我会说先理解这两个：\n\n1. **`channels.feishu.groupPolicy=open`**\n   - 这是“谁能对你说话”的入口问题\n\n2. **`sandbox=off + workspaceOnly=false`**\n   - 这是“你听了话之后能做多大动作”的权限问题\n\n这两个一前一后，刚好构成完整风险链。\n\n---\n\n如果你愿意，我下一条可以继续只做解释版，给你出一个：\n\n**“风险项 → 对应配置 → 改成什么值最稳妥” 的纯说明表**\n\n不改机器，只给你决策参考。"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":37746,"output":1481,"cacheRead":2560,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41787,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773712483772}}
{"type":"message","id":"e8e085a5","parentId":"b15e77fb","timestamp":"2026-03-17T01:56:49.150Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b54bf00cd60bcb2848014d5d7c4f\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"sender\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-17 09:56 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\",\n  \"name\": \"ou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b54bf00cd60bcb2848014d5d7c4f]\nou_664eb5978d7a2e16127187d1c18827d3: 改群组策略 禁用群聊"}],"timestamp":1773712609148}}
{"type":"message","id":"b6e76aa0","parentId":"e8e085a5","timestamp":"2026-03-17T01:56:59.139Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Evaluating configuration changes**\n\nI need to explicitly confirm any configuration changes. First, I should inspect the relevant schema before making edits. There’s also the option of looking into the feishu-channel-rules skill, which always seems to be active in Llark conversations. I wonder if it applies here? Well, the user might be asking about a config change that doesn't align with any skills. Maybe health checks are relevant, since it relates to security hardening? I need to read more about it.\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_79WODuI6dCYxPQjObBOHx3h9","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"~/.npm-global/lib/node_modules/openclaw/skills/healthcheck/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":40100,"output":206,"cacheRead":2560,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42866,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773712609149}}
{"type":"message","id":"d218bee3","parentId":"b6e76aa0","timestamp":"2026-03-17T01:56:59.151Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_79WODuI6dCYxPQjObBOHx3h9","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: healthcheck\ndescription: Host security hardening and risk-tolerance configuration for OpenClaw deployments. Use when a user asks for security audits, firewall/SSH/update hardening, risk posture, exposure review, OpenClaw cron scheduling for periodic checks, or version status checks on a machine running OpenClaw (laptop, workstation, Pi, VPS).\n---\n\n# OpenClaw Host Hardening\n\n## Overview\n\nAssess and harden the host running OpenClaw, then align it to a user-defined risk tolerance without breaking access. Use OpenClaw security tooling as a first-class signal, but treat OS hardening as a separate, explicit set of steps.\n\n## Core rules\n\n- Recommend running this skill with a state-of-the-art model (e.g., Opus 4.5, GPT 5.2+). The agent should self-check the current model and suggest switching if below that level; do not block execution.\n- Require explicit approval before any state-changing action.\n- Do not modify remote access settings without confirming how the user connects.\n- Prefer reversible, staged changes with a rollback plan.\n- Never claim OpenClaw changes the host firewall, SSH, or OS updates; it does not.\n- If role/identity is unknown, provide recommendations only.\n- Formatting: every set of user choices must be numbered so the user can reply with a single digit.\n- System-level backups are recommended; try to verify status.\n\n## Workflow (follow in order)\n\n### 0) Model self-check (non-blocking)\n\nBefore starting, check the current model. If it is below state-of-the-art (e.g., Opus 4.5, GPT 5.2+), recommend switching. Do not block execution.\n\n### 1) Establish context (read-only)\n\nTry to infer 1–5 from the environment before asking. Prefer simple, non-technical questions if you need confirmation.\n\nDetermine (in order):\n\n1. OS and version (Linux/macOS/Windows), container vs host.\n2. Privilege level (root/admin vs user).\n3. Access path (local console, SSH, RDP, tailnet).\n4. Network exposure (public IP, reverse proxy, tunnel).\n5. OpenClaw gateway status and bind address.\n6. Backup system and status (e.g., Time Machine, system images, snapshots).\n7. Deployment context (local mac app, headless gateway host, remote gateway, container/CI).\n8. Disk encryption status (FileVault/LUKS/BitLocker).\n9. OS automatic security updates status.\n   Note: these are not blocking items, but are highly recommended, especially if OpenClaw can access sensitive data.\n10. Usage mode for a personal assistant with full access (local workstation vs headless/remote vs other).\n\nFirst ask once for permission to run read-only checks. If granted, run them by default and only ask questions for items you cannot infer or verify. Do not ask for information already visible in runtime or command output. Keep the permission ask as a single sentence, and list follow-up info needed as an unordered list (not numbered) unless you are presenting selectable choices.\n\nIf you must ask, use non-technical prompts:\n\n- “Are you using a Mac, Windows PC, or Linux?”\n- “Are you logged in directly on the machine, or connecting from another computer?”\n- “Is this machine reachable from the public internet, or only on your home/network?”\n- “Do you have backups enabled (e.g., Time Machine), and are they current?”\n- “Is disk encryption turned on (FileVault/BitLocker/LUKS)?”\n- “Are automatic security updates enabled?”\n- “How do you use this machine?”\n  Examples:\n  - Personal machine shared with the assistant\n  - Dedicated local machine for the assistant\n  - Dedicated remote machine/server accessed remotely (always on)\n  - Something else?\n\nOnly ask for the risk profile after system context is known.\n\nIf the user grants read-only permission, run the OS-appropriate checks by default. If not, offer them (numbered). Examples:\n\n1. OS: `uname -a`, `sw_vers`, `cat /etc/os-release`.\n2. Listening ports:\n   - Linux: `ss -ltnup` (or `ss -ltnp` if `-u` unsupported).\n   - macOS: `lsof -nP -iTCP -sTCP:LISTEN`.\n3. Firewall status:\n   - Linux: `ufw status`, `firewall-cmd --state`, `nft list ruleset` (pick what is installed).\n   - macOS: `/usr/libexec/ApplicationFirewall/socketfilterfw --getglobalstate` and `pfctl -s info`.\n4. Backups (macOS): `tmutil status` (if Time Machine is used).\n\n### 2) Run OpenClaw security audits (read-only)\n\nAs part of the default read-only checks, run `openclaw security audit --deep`. Only offer alternatives if the user requests them:\n\n1. `openclaw security audit` (faster, non-probing)\n2. `openclaw security audit --json` (structured output)\n\nOffer to apply OpenClaw safe defaults (numbered):\n\n1. `openclaw security audit --fix`\n\nBe explicit that `--fix` only tightens OpenClaw defaults and file permissions. It does not change host firewall, SSH, or OS update policies.\n\nIf browser control is enabled, recommend that 2FA be enabled on all important accounts, with hardware keys preferred and SMS not sufficient.\n\n### 3) Check OpenClaw version/update status (read-only)\n\nAs part of the default read-only checks, run `openclaw update status`.\n\nReport the current channel and whether an update is available.\n\n### 4) Determine risk tolerance (after system context)\n\nAsk the user to pick or confirm a risk posture and any required open services/ports (numbered choices below).\nDo not pigeonhole into fixed profiles; if the user prefers, capture requirements instead of choosing a profile.\nOffer suggested profiles as optional defaults (numbered). Note that most users pick Home/Workstation Balanced:\n\n1. Home/Workstation Balanced (most common): firewall on with reasonable defaults, remote access restricted to LAN or tailnet.\n2. VPS Hardened: deny-by-default inbound firewall, minimal open ports, key-only SSH, no root login, automatic security updates.\n3. Developer Convenience: more local services allowed, explicit exposure warnings, still audited.\n4. Custom: user-defined constraints (services, exposure, update cadence, access methods).\n\n### 5) Produce a remediation plan\n\nProvide a plan that includes:\n\n- Target profile\n- Current posture summary\n- Gaps vs target\n- Step-by-step remediation with exact commands\n- Access-preservation strategy and rollback\n- Risks and potential lockout scenarios\n- Least-privilege notes (e.g., avoid admin usage, tighten ownership/permissions where safe)\n- Credential hygiene notes (location of OpenClaw creds, prefer disk encryption)\n\nAlways show the plan before any changes.\n\n### 6) Offer execution options\n\nOffer one of these choices (numbered so users can reply with a single digit):\n\n1. Do it for me (guided, step-by-step approvals)\n2. Show plan only\n3. Fix only critical issues\n4. Export commands for later\n\n### 7) Execute with confirmations\n\nFor each step:\n\n- Show the exact command\n- Explain impact and rollback\n- Confirm access will remain available\n- Stop on unexpected output and ask for guidance\n\n### 8) Verify and report\n\nRe-check:\n\n- Firewall status\n- Listening ports\n- Remote access still works\n- OpenClaw security audit (re-run)\n\nDeliver a final posture report and note any deferred items.\n\n## Required confirmations (always)\n\nRequire explicit approval for:\n\n- Firewall rule changes\n- Opening/closing ports\n- SSH/RDP configuration changes\n- Installing/removing packages\n- Enabling/disabling services\n- User/group modifications\n- Scheduling tasks or startup persistence\n- Update policy changes\n- Access to sensitive files or credentials\n\nIf unsure, ask.\n\n## Periodic checks\n\nAfter OpenClaw install or first hardening pass, run at least one baseline audit and version check:\n\n- `openclaw security audit`\n- `openclaw security audit --deep`\n- `openclaw update status`\n\nOngoing monitoring is recommended. Use the OpenClaw cron tool/CLI to schedule periodic audits (Gateway scheduler). Do not create scheduled tasks without explicit approval. Store outputs in a user-approved location and avoid secrets in logs.\nWhen scheduling headless cron runs, include a note in the output that instructs the user to call `healthcheck` so issues can be fixed.\n\n### Required prompt to schedule (always)\n\nAfter any audit or hardening pass, explicitly offer scheduling and require a direct response. Use a short prompt like (numbered):\n\n1. “Do you want me to schedule periodic audits (e.g., daily/weekly) via `openclaw cron add`?”\n\nIf the user says yes, ask for:\n\n- cadence (daily/weekly), preferred time window, and output location\n- whether to also schedule `openclaw update status`\n\nUse a stable cron job name so updates are deterministic. Prefer exact names:\n\n- `healthcheck:security-audit`\n- `healthcheck:update-status`\n\nBefore creating, `openclaw cron list` and match on exact `name`. If found, `openclaw cron edit <id> ...`.\nIf not found, `openclaw cron add --name <name> ...`.\n\nAlso offer a periodic version check so the user can decide when to update (numbered):\n\n1. `openclaw update status` (preferred for source checkouts and channels)\n2. `npm view openclaw version` (published npm version)\n\n## OpenClaw command accuracy\n\nUse only supported commands and flags:\n\n- `openclaw security audit [--deep] [--fix] [--json]`\n- `openclaw status` / `openclaw status --deep`\n- `openclaw health --json`\n- `openclaw update status`\n- `openclaw cron add|list|runs|run`\n\nDo not invent CLI flags or imply OpenClaw enforces host firewall/SSH policies.\n\n## Logging and audit trail\n\nRecord:\n\n- Gateway identity and role\n- Plan ID and timestamp\n- Approved steps and exact commands\n- Exit codes and files modified (best effort)\n\nRedact secrets. Never log tokens or full credential contents.\n\n## Memory writes (conditional)\n\nOnly write to memory files when the user explicitly opts in and the session is a private/local workspace\n(per `docs/reference/templates/AGENTS.md`). Otherwise provide a redacted, paste-ready summary the user can\ndecide to save elsewhere.\n\nFollow the durable-memory prompt format used by OpenClaw compaction:\n\n- Write lasting notes to `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md`.\n\nAfter each audit/hardening run, if opted-in, append a short, dated summary to `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md`\n(what was checked, key findings, actions taken, any scheduled cron jobs, key decisions,\nand all commands executed). Append-only: never overwrite existing entries.\nRedact sensitive host details (usernames, hostnames, IPs, serials, service names, tokens).\nIf there are durable preferences or decisions (risk posture, allowed ports, update policy),\nalso update `MEMORY.md` (long-term memory is optional and only used in private sessions).\n\nIf the session cannot write to the workspace, ask for permission or provide exact entries\nthe user can paste into the memory files.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773712619148}}
{"type":"message","id":"bf075c70","parentId":"d218bee3","timestamp":"2026-03-17T01:57:12.233Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Patching configuration updates**\n\nI need to comply with an explicit request to change the configuration, so I'll start by inspecting the schema at the specific path according to the instructions. I think I already checked the groupPolicy path; that might be enough. I’ll patch the config next. It’s possible that the channels.feishu.groupAllowFrom setting isn't needed if it's disabled. Additionally, I need to create a human-readable note since patching triggers a restart, and I should probably confirm with the user that this is what they wanted.\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"我直接把 Feishu 群聊策略改成禁用。这个改动会触发 OpenClaw 重启，私聊不受影响，群里将不能再触发。"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_vAQ5uDKNKRB91lYI4ztyFfD5","name":"gateway","arguments":{"action":"config.patch","patch":{"channels":{"feishu":{"groupPolicy":"disabled"}}},"note":"已按要求禁用 Feishu 群聊触发策略（groupPolicy=disabled），重启后生效。"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":6248,"output":270,"cacheRead":38400,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":44918,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773712619152}}
